Raw dev notes -- Auto-GIT: Trusting the Machine (or, How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Auto-Commit)

Okay, so this past week has been a deep dive into automating my personal Git workflow, which I'm calling "Auto-GIT." The whole point of this project is to basically eliminate my own forgetfulness. I want my personal work to always be backed up, and my dev environment configs (like my `~/.claude` setup) to be perfectly consistent across all my machines, without me having to think about it. It's about reducing mental overhead and making sure I never lose a day's work because I forgot to push.

This period kicked off with just the bare bones: a daily Git sync script and a basic installer. But it quickly escalated. The installer got a massive upgrade – it now automatically generates an SSH key, rewrites any existing HTTPS remotes to use SSH (which is crucial for unattended automation), and even pops open the GitHub page so I can easily add the new key. I also made sure the installer was idempotent, which is always a fun little puzzle to solve, so running it multiple times won't mess things up. It'll only open the browser if it actually generates a *new* key, which is a nice UX touch.

Then came the syncing features. I started with a dedicated sync for my `~/.claude` config, pushing it to a special repo. Initially, it was daily, but I quickly bumped that up to hourly, adding a "time-aware push window" to make sure it's not pushing at weird times or when I'm actively working on something else.

The biggest, most nerve-wracking feature was implementing hourly auto-commits for my personal repos. This is where the "trusting the machine" part really comes in. To make this even remotely palatable, I had to build in what I'm calling "tier-3 safety." This includes a local backup before any push, a dry-run mode, a "big-diff guard" to prevent accidentally pushing massive, unintended changes, and a 7-day window for pushes. The idea is to catch any potential disasters before they hit the remote.

Honestly, the hardest part was wrestling with the fear of automation gone wrong. Auto-committing and pushing is inherently risky. Defining what constitutes a "big diff" for the guard was tricky – it's a heuristic, not a perfect science. And making sure the 7-day window logic was solid, so I don't accidentally push something ancient or miss something recent, took a lot of careful thought. Idempotency, as always, was a bit of a brain-bender, especially when dealing with file system changes and Git operations. The "time-aware push window" also had its moments of "wait, what time zone is this running in?" kind of confusion.

It's a weird mix of excitement and anxiety. Excitement because this is exactly the kind of automation I crave, but anxiety because I'm literally giving a script permission to commit and push my work. It's a huge step in learning to trust my own code, and to build in enough safeguards that I *can* trust it. This project feels like a direct response to my own human fallibility, and it's incredibly satisfying to build tools that make my life easier and my workflow more robust. It's a personal growth moment, realizing I can build these safety nets.

Next up: Refining the safety features and expanding to more config files.
